## 4. Lead Scoring

Define how you rank prospects so reps prioritize the right ones.

### Scoring criteria

| Factor | Weight | How to measure | Source |
|--------|--------|---------------|--------|
| Organization size | | (employees, units, revenue, locations) | (website, public filings, industry data) |
| Annual volume | | (how many times they'd use your product/year) | (public data, industry averages) |
| Budget signals | | (recent funding, grants, budget increases) | (news, government records) |
| Technology fit | | (are they already using adjacent tools?) | (job postings, tech stack tools) |
| Engagement signals | | (website visit, content download, event attendance) | (your analytics) |
| Timing signals | | (contract renewal, new hire, audit, incident) | (news, job boards) |

### Tier definitions

| Tier | Label | Criteria | Priority |
|------|-------|----------|----------|
| 1 | | | Highest — founder handles these personally |
| 2 | | | High — senior rep, bespoke research |
| 3 | | | Standard — rep with council scoring |
| 4 | | | Low — generic template, batch outreach |

### Volume-to-tier formula

How do you calculate which tier a prospect falls into?

(Example: "EMS runs per year x 0.02 = estimated intubations. 200+ = Tier 2, 50-199 = Tier 3, under 50 = Tier 4.")

